    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Tarquinius Priscus, primò Popularis ad gratiam: deinde Regius ad magnitudinem. Ab initio, Roma[e] omnia venalia: etiam Regna.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                    <location name="Rome"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tarquinius Priscus was first active in the community to gain popularity, and then in royal circles to increase his status. 
                From the beginning everything in Rome was for sale, even the power of political control.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Hactenùs Anci Historia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Ancus Marcius"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Historia" type="curved"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>So far the history of Ancus Marcius.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>5. Tarquinij Prisci historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>5. Royal history of Tarquinus Priscus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>} nota distinctionem Regni, et Reipub[licae].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Note the difference between the kingdom and the republic.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Qui philosophi enituerint regnante apud Romanos Tarquinio Prisco; apud Hebra[e]os Sedechia; cum Hierusalem capta est, 
                        templumq[ue] subuersu[m]. August. l. 18. c. 25. de ciuitate Dei. ex Eusebio. nempe septem Sapientes. (qui tame[n] s[upr]a regnante Romulo).
                        Item Anaximander, et Anaximenes, et Xenophanes physici. Tunc et Pythagoras, ex quo coeperunt appellari philosophi. 
                        Consulendae chronologiae. Certè temporibus regum Cyri, Cro[e]si, Pisistrati, florueru[n]t septem sapientes. 
                        Cyro autem rege, populus Juda[e]us est solutus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Zedekiah"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Eusebius"/>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Anaximander"/>
                    <person name="Anaximenes"/>
                    <person name="Xenophanes"/>
                    <person name="Pythagoras"/>
                    <person name="Cyrus the Great"/>
                    <person name="Pisistratus"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <location name="Jerusalem"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000026" text="s[upr]a"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>What philosophers achieved distinction during the reign of Tarquinius Priscus over the Romans and Zedekiah over the Hebrews, 
                at the time when Jerusalem was captured and the temple overthrown: Augustine, 'City of God', bk. 18, c. 25, based on Eusebius. 
                This concerns the seven sages, of course, (about whom see above, during the reign of Romulus), and also the natural scientists Anaximander, 
                Anaximenes and Xenophanes. During that period also Pythagoras lived, from whose time such men began to be called philosophers. 
                One should consider the chronology. Certainly the seven sages thrived in the period of the kings Cyrus, Croesus, Pisistratus. 
                And in fact while Cyrus was king the Jewish people were released.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
